Exactly, that is the right pattern: a human-in-the-loop recovery gate.

Real model should be:

Action fails.
Planner pauses at a safe point.
UI pops allowed recovery choices for that failure context.
Operator selects what was physically done.
System applies a deterministic world patch from that choice.
Planner resumes from updated world (replan, don’t continue blindly).
For your decap case, each option must map to a strict world update:

Operator re-capped and put sample back to centrifuge rack:
location = centrifuge rack slot
cap_state = CAPPED
DECAP completed = false
Operator moved sample to IH-500 slot but still capped:
location = IH500 slot
cap_state = CAPPED
DECAP completed = false
Operator decapped and moved sample to IH-500 slot:
location = IH500 slot
cap_state = DECAPPED
DECAP completed = true
Scalability implication:

Don’t hardcode this per workflow step.
Create a recovery policy table keyed by:
process + failed_step + station/device.
Each entry defines:
operator options + required world patch + resume mode (retry/skip/replan).
This scales well because new devices/failures only add policy entries, not deep logic rewrites.
The critical success factor is consistency: operator choice must always produce one unambiguous world state update.





How to build the project from scratch :

If rebuilding from zero, best choice is:

Hierarchical fine-grained BT (not fully flat, not coarse monolith).
Reusable subtrees for atomic robot behaviors (Navigate+Scan, PickSample, PlaceSample, ProcessAt3FG, PickRack, Push/PullRack).
Policy-driven recovery wrapper around each physical action:
retry
skip_action
skip_sample
manual_outcome_patch
abort
Event-sourced world state as source of truth (every action and operator decision logged, resumable).
Planner and executor separated:
Planner proposes next intent from world state.
Executor runs intent with BT + recovery.
Resource/locking model (robot arm, gripper, station/device) so one blocked sample does not freeze everything.
Explicit resume model (run_id, action_id, pending_recovery_id) so restart/reconnect is deterministic.
Short version: choose a hybrid architecture: macro phases + fine-grained executable leaves + external recovery policy.
That gives you the best scalability, traceability, and operator-assisted robustness.